  "prompt": "How can you determine the orbital notation of iron?",
  "response": "To determine the orbital notation of iron, follow these steps:\n\n1. Find the atomic number of iron (26)\n\n2. Determine the electron configuration using aufbau principle:\n\u2022 1s\u00b2 (2 electrons)\n\u2022 2s\u00b2 (2 more electrons)\n\u2022 2p\u2076 (6 more electrons)\n\u2022 3s\u00b2 (2 more electrons)\n\u2022 3p\u2076 (6 more electrons)\n\u2022 4s\u00b2 (2 more electrons)\n\u2022 3d\u2076 (6 more electrons)\n\n3. The full electron configuration is: 1s\u00b2 2s\u00b2 2p\u2076 3s\u00b2 3p\u2076 4s\u00b2 3d\u2076\n\n4. Orbital notation shows electrons as arrows:\n\u2022 Spin up (\u2191) and spin down (\u2193) electrons\n\u2022 Following Pauli exclusion principle\n\u2022 Maximum 2 electrons per orbital with opposite spins\n\n5. For iron's orbital notation, the 4s and 3d orbitals would be partially filled with arrows representing electrons\n\nThe final orbital notation would show the specific electron arrangement in each orbital, consistent with the electron configuration.",
